<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why These Companies Work Better for Short Seasons</h2>

  <h3>They Make Early Varieties Easy to Find</h3>
  <p>
    In many seed catalogs, early varieties are buried. The best companies for short seasons make them obvious.
  </p>

  <p>
    Johnny’s and Territorial, for example, tend to offer stronger filtering, clearer descriptions, and more consistent early options across crops.
  </p>

  <h3>They Provide Reliable Days-to-Maturity</h3>
  <p>
    When your season is tight, inaccurate timing data is a real problem.
  </p>

  <p>
    Companies that serve market growers or serious home gardeners tend to provide more consistent maturity timelines, which makes planning much easier.
  </p>

  <h3>They Have Depth Across Crops — Not Just One Category</h3>
  <p>
    A single early tomato is not enough. You need early beans, cucumbers, squash, greens, and more.
  </p>

  <p>
    The best seed companies for short seasons offer multiple fast options across the entire garden, not just isolated crops.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>The Problem with Many Popular Seed Companies</h2>

  <p>
    Many widely known seed companies are optimized for:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>long growing seasons</li>
    <li>maximum yield potential</li>
    <li>large, diverse catalogs</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    That often leads to:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>longer maturity timelines</li>
    <li>less emphasis on early production</li>
    <li>varieties that struggle in cooler conditions</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These companies can still work — but they require much more careful selection.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How to Choose the Right Seed Company for Your Situation</h2>

  <h3>If You Have a Very Short Season</h3>
  <p>
    Focus on companies with the strongest early-maturing selections and the most reliable timing data.
  </p>

  <h3>If You Garden in a Cool Climate</h3>
  <p>
    Prioritize companies that trial or operate in cooler regions, where varieties are selected for performance under lower heat.
  </p>

  <h3>If You Want Simpler Decisions</h3>
  <p>
    Choose catalogs that make early varieties easy to identify instead of requiring deep comparison.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Choosing Based on Popularity</h3>
  <p>
    The most well-known seed companies are not always the best fit for short seasons.
  </p>

  <h3>Focusing on Variety Names Instead of Timing</h3>
  <p>
    Maturity time determines whether a crop succeeds — not how appealing it looks in the catalog.
  </p>

  <h3>Trying to Grow Long-Season Crops Anyway</h3>
  <p>
    This is one of the biggest sources of disappointment in short-season gardens.
  </p>

  <h3>Not Comparing Across Companies</h3>
  <p>
    Some catalogs are noticeably faster overall — and that difference compounds across your entire garden.
  </p>
</section>

